# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-whitman-cross
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst has three census-designated places: Amherst Center, North Amherst, and South Amherst.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is part of the Springfield, Massachusetts Metropolitan Statistical Area.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Lying 22 miles (35 km) north of the city of Springfield, Amherst is considered the northernmost town in the Hartford–Springfield Metropolitan Region, "The Knowledge Corridor".
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is also located in the Pioneer Valley, which encompasses Hampshire, Hampden and Franklin counties.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The name of the town is pronounced without the *h* ("AM-erst") by natives and long-time residents, giving rise to the local saying, "only the 'h' is silent", in reference both to the pronunciation and to the town's politically active populace.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The earliest known document of the lands now comprising Amherst is the deed of purchase dated December 1658 between John Pynchon of Springfield and three native inhabitants, referred to as Umpanchla, Quonquont, and Chickwalopp.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] According to the deed, "ye Indians of Nolwotogg (Norwottuck) upon ye River of Quinecticott (Connecticut)" sold the entire area in exchange for "two Hundred fatham of Wampam & Twenty fatham, and one large Coate at Eight fatham wch Chickwollop set of, of trusts, besides severall small giftes" [*sic*].
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst was first visited by Europeans no later than 1665, when Nathaniel Dickinson surveyed the lands for its mother town Hadley.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The first permanent English settlements arrived in 1727.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] It remained a part of Hadley, even when it gained precinct status in 1734, before becoming a township in 1759.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] When it incorporated, the colonial governor assigned the town the name "Amherst" after Jeffery Amherst, 1st Baron Amherst.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Many a colonial governor at the time scattered his name during the influx of new town applications, which is why several towns in the Northeast bear the name.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst was Commander-in-Chief of the forces of North America during the French and Indian War who, according to popular legend, singlehandedly won Canada for the British and banished France from North America.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Popular belief has it that he supported the American side in the Revolutionary War and resigned his commission rather than fight for the British.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Baron Amherst actually remained in the service of the Crown during the war—albeit in Great Britain rather than North America—where he organized the defense against the proposed Franco-Spanish Armada of 1779.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Nonetheless, his previous service in the French and Indian War meant he remained popular in New England.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is also infamous for recommending, in a letter to a subordinate, the use of smallpox-covered blankets in warfare against the Native Americans along with any "other method that can serve to Extirpate this Execrable Race".
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] For this reason, there have been occasional ad hoc movements to rename the town.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst celebrated its 250th anniversary in 2009.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The Amherst 250th Anniversary Celebration Committee and Amherst Historical Society organized events, including a book published by the Historical Society and written by Elizabeth M.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In 2021 the City Council voted to establish the Amherst African Heritage Reparation Assembly to study reparations for the town's black residents.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In 2022, at the Assembly's suggestion, the City Council approved $2,000,000 of initial funding for reparations.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The Town converted from an open town meeting to a representative town meeting form in 1938.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In 1953, Amherst voters passed the "Town Manager Act", which established the office of a town manager and reduced a number of elected positions.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In 1995, a charter commission was approved to study Amherst's government; the charter majority recommended a seven-person Council and a mayor, while also maintaining a reduced size representative Town Meeting (150).
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] This proposal failed in two successive votes.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In 2001, the League of Women Voters Amherst made a number of recommendations that were adopted in 2001 in the form of a revised "Amherst Town Government Act".
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] An effort shortly thereafter to amend the charter to eliminate the town meeting, and establish an elected mayor and a nine-member Town Council, was rejected by voters twice, first in spring 2003 by fourteen votes and again on March 29, 2005 by 252 votes.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In 2016, a charter commission was approved to study Amherst's government.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] A majority of commissioners proposed a charter that would establish a 13-member council with no mayor.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] This proposal was voted on the March 27, 2018 local ballot, and was passed by over 1,000 votes, a 58% majority.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The new town council was sworn in on December 2, 2018.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] According to the United States Census Bureau, Amherst has a total area of 27.7 square miles (71.8 km2), of which 27.6 square miles (71.5 km2) are land and 0.12 square miles (0.3 km2), or 0.48%, are water.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The town is bordered by Hadley to the west, Sunderland and Leverett to the north, Shutesbury, Pelham, and Belchertown to the east, and Granby and South Hadley to the south.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The highest point in the town is on the northern shoulder of Mount Norwottuck at the southern border of the town; the peak is in Granby but the town's high point is a few yards away and is about 1,100 feet (340 m).
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] This point is located in the Mount Holyoke Range, which forms the so-called "Tofu Curtain".
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is nearly equidistant from Massachusetts' borders with Connecticut and Vermont.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst's ZIP Code of 01002 is the second-lowest number in the continental United States after Agawam (not counting codes used for specific government buildings such as the IRS).
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst has a marginal hot-summer humid continental climate (*Köppen: Dfa*), with July means hovering around 71.7 °F (22.1 °C).
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Winters are cold and snowy, although daytime temperatures often remain above freezing.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Under the 2012 USDA Plant Hardiness Zone system, Amherst (ZIP Code 01002) is in zone 5b; however, Amherst closely borders zone 6a, which penetrates into Massachusetts in the Connecticut River Valley, and climate change may be shifting those zones.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] As of the 2020 U.S. census, there were 39,263 people, 9,700 households, and 4,124 families residing in the town.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The racial makeup of the town was 66.6% White, 5.1% Black or African American, 0.3% Native American, 14.4% Asian, 2.2% some other race, and 11.4% from two or more races.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] 9% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Of the 9,700 households in the town, 17.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 34.4% were headed by married couples living together, 2.5% had a male householder with no spouse present, 5.6% had a female householder with no spouse present, and 57.5% were non-families.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Of all households, 35.8% were made up of individuals, and 11.3% were someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The average household size was 2.21 and the average family size was 2.87.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In the town, 5.1% of the population were aged 14 and younger, 61.6% were from 15 to 24, 12.4% were from 25 to 44, 10.6% were from 45 to 64, and 10.2% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] For every 100 females, there were 95.8 males.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.1 males.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The estimated median annual income for a household in the town was $66,968, and the median income for a family was $150,061.About 7.6% of families and 23.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 17.4% of those under age 18 and 4.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Of residents 25 years old or older, 53.0% have a graduate or professional degree, 22.6% have a bachelor's degree and only 3.1% did not graduate from high school.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The largest industry is education, health, and social services, in which 50.6% of employed persons work.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] As of the 2010 U.S. census, there were 37,819 people, 9,259 households, and 4,484 families residing in the town.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The racial makeup of the town was 76.9% White, 5.4% Black or African American, 0.2% Native American, 10.9% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 2.4% some other race, and 4.1% from two or more races.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] 7.3% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Of the 9,259 households in the town, 23.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.6% were headed by married couples living together, 16.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 51.6% were non-families.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Of all households, 27.3% were made up of individuals, and 9.7% were someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The average household size was 2.44 and the average family size was 2.88.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In the town, 10.0% of the population were under the age of 18, 55.7% were from 18 to 24, 13.3% were from 25 to 44, 13.6% were from 45 to 64, and 7.4% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.7 males.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] For the period 2011–2015, the estimated median annual income for a household in the town was $48,059, and the median income for a family was $96,005.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Male full-time workers had a median income of $64,750 versus $39,278 for females.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The per capita income for the town was $18,905.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] About 8.7% of families and 34.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 18.2% of those under age 18 and 4.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Of residents 25 years old or older, 41.7% have a graduate or professional degree, and only 4.9% did not graduate from high school.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The largest industry is education, health, and social services, in which 51.9% of employed persons work.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] These statistics given above include some but not all of the large student population, roughly 30,000 in 2010, many of whom only reside in the town part of the year.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is home to thousands of part-time and full-time residents associated with the University of Massachusetts Amherst, Amherst College, and Hampshire College.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Data is from the 2009–2013 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Major employers in Amherst include University of Massachusetts Amherst, Amherst College, William D.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Mullins Memorial Center, Hampshire College, and Amherst-Pelham Regional School District.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst has a town council for its legislative branch and a town manager for its executive branch.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The town manager is appointed by the town council.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst's town council consists of ten district councilors and three councilors-at-large.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Two district councilors are elected from each of five districts in Amherst.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The three councilors-at-large are elected by the whole town.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Each councilor serves a two-year term, except for the first council, where each member will serve a three-year term.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst also has a five-member housing authority in which three of the five members are elected by voters.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In the Massachusetts Senate Amherst is in the "Hampshire, Franklin and Worcester" district, represented by Democratic State Senator Jo Comerford since January 2019.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In the Massachusetts House of Representatives Amherst is in the 3rd Hampshire district, represented by Democratic State Representative Mindy Domb since January 2019.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is part of the Eighth Massachusetts Governor's Council district and has been represented by Tara Jacobs since January 2023.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst is represented at the federal level by an all-Democratic delegation, including Senators Elizabeth Warren and Ed Markey, and by Representative Jim McGovern of the Second Congressional District of Massachusetts.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Voter registration data is from the state election enrollment statistics.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Like many college towns, Amherst leans heavily Democratic.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In each of the presidential elections from 2012 to 2020, more than 80% of Amherst's votes went to the Democratic candidate.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The last Republican to win Amherst on the Presidential level was Richard Nixon in 1960.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In the 2020 United States presidential election, Democrat Joe Biden received 90.3 percent of the vote to incumbent Republican Donald Trump's 7.4 percent.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] In the 2000 United States presidential election, Amherst was one of a small number of places that delivered more votes for Green Party candidate Ralph Nader (who took 24% of the vote) than Republican candidate George W.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The town is part of the Amherst Regional School District along with Leverett, Pelham, and Shutesbury.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amherst has three elementary schools: Crocker Farm Elementary School, Fort River Elementary School, and Wildwood Elementary School serving K–6.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Students in Amherst then attend Amherst Regional Middle School for grades 7–8.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] High school students then attend Amherst Regional High School.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] There are three tertiary institutions located in the town: the public University of Massachusetts Amherst (the flagship of the UMass system), and two private liberal arts colleges—Amherst College and Hampshire College.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The Pioneer Valley Transit Authority, funded by local governments and the Five College Consortium, provides public transportation in the area, operated by University of Massachusetts Transportation Services.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Service runs well into the early morning hours on weekends when school is in session.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Students attending any colleges in the Five Colleges Consortium have a fee included in their tuition bills (service fee for UMass Amherst students and student activity fees for the other colleges) for each semester that prepays their bus fares for the semester.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] UMass Transit buses operate via a proof-of-payment system, in which there are random inspections of student identification cards and bus passes and transfers.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Peter Pan Bus Lines provides service between Amherst and Springfield, Boston, and other locations in New England.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Megabus provides service between New York City, Amherst, and Burlington, Vermont.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Amtrak rail service is available in nearby Northampton on the *Vermonter* service between Washington, D.C., and St.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] More frequent Amtrak service to New York City and Washington, D.C., is available from Union Station in Springfield.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] The closest major domestic and limited international air service is available through Bradley International Airport (BDL) in Windsor Locks, Connecticut.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Bradley is located approximately one hour's driving time from Amherst.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Major international service is available through Logan International Airport (BOS) in Boston, 90 miles (140 km) away.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] General aviation service is close by, at Northampton Airport, Westover Metropolitan Airport, and Turners Falls Airport.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] Since 1997, the local newspaper, the *Amherst Bulletin*, has published a weekly log of phone calls received by the Amherst Police Department.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] This police report, whose tone is deadpan and often unintentionally humorous, has been the subject of at least two books and a 2002 article in *Harper's Magazine*, "Gone When Police Got There".
[src:charles-whitman-cross/amherst-massachusetts] For example, an entry from the March 27, 2015 police report reads: "2:48 a.m.—An Ann Whalen Apartments resident awoke to find someone on her balcony looking into her bedroom.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Cross was born September 1, 1854, in Amherst, Massachusetts, to Maria Mason Cross and the Rev.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Later his family moved to Waverly, Iowa, where he graduated high school.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] In 1872 he entered the Scientific Course at Amherst College.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] After earning a Bachelor of Science degree in 1875, he remained at Amherst doing post-graduate studies in science.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] He attended the University of Göttingen from 1877 to 1878, when he transferred to Leipzig University.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] There he studied under Ferdinand Zirkel and earned his Ph.D. in 1880.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] After completing his Ph.D., Cross returned to the United States and began a career with the U.S.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Geological Survey that would last until his retirement in 1925.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] From 1880 to 1888 he was based in Denver, Colorado, after which he moved to Washington, D.C., where he headed the Survey's petrology section.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Cross was a petrologist, and much of his field work focused on rocks.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Most of this was done in Colorado, in rugged terrain with few roads.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] His greatest work was on the San Juan Mountains beginning in 1895.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] He also worked in the Leucite Hills of Wyoming and in Hawaii.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Besides his substantial field work, Cross was known for his pioneering research in normative mineralogy.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Iddings, Louis Valentine Pirsson, and Henry Stephens Washington, he devised a measurement of the chemical composition of rocks that came to be known as the CIPW norm, after their initials.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Published in a 1903 book, their method was more quantitative than previous approaches and introduced a novel nomenclature system.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] While other petrologists generally judged their nomenclature to be too detailed and cumbersome, they embraced the quantitative approach of calculating a "norm" based on a rock's chemical composition, and the CIPW norm remains a staple of petrology.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Cross helped organize the National Research Council.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] He was a member from 1918 to 1922, treasurer from 1918 to 1919, and vice chairman of its Division of Geology and Geography in 1918.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] He was among several geologists who persuaded the Carnegie Institution of Washington to establish its Geophysical Laboratory.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] In 1910 he organized the Petrologists' Club, whose first meetings took place in his home.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Cross was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1908 and was its treasurer from 1911 to 1919. he was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1915.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] He was a member of the Geological Society of America and was its president in 1918.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] In 1925, his alma mater Amherst College awarded him an honorary Doctor of Sciences degree.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] On November 7, 1895, Cross married Virginia Stevens, daughter of Moses T.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] Cross died April 20, 1949, in Chevy Chase, Maryland.
[src:charles-whitman-cross/charles-whitman-cross] At the time of his death he was the oldest member of the National Academy of Sciences and the oldest living alumnus of Amherst College.
